<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="595" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="0.[151,1436,1485,2028]" pageId="0" pageNumber="595">
<emphasis box="[197,313,1763,1786]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="595" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,306,1763,1786]" pageId="0" pageNumber="595">Diagnosis</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[319,470,1763,1786]" class="Exobasidiomycetes" family="Curculionidae" genus="Meira" kingdom="Fungi" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="595" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[319,384,1763,1786]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="595">Meira</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
, habitus short oval, with pterygia hardly prominent, antennae very robust, pronotum hardly transverse, elytra with setae slightly elongate raised or semi-erect.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="1" lastPageNumber="596" pageId="0" pageNumber="595" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="0.[151,1436,1485,2028]" pageId="0" pageNumber="595">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,336,1832,1855]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="595" reason="1">Description.</emphasis>
Species of intermediate size as compared with other 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Jacquelin du Val" baseAuthorityYear="1852" box="[911,976,1832,1855]" class="Exobasidiomycetes" family="Curculionidae" genus="Meira" kingdom="Fungi" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="595" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[911,976,1832,1855]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="595">Meira</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(2.6-3.4 mm), and overall shape short and ovate (
<figureCitation box="[224,300,1867,1890]" captionStart="PLATE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,238,1748,1771]" captionTargetBox="[271,1333,789,1724]" captionTargetId="figure-279@1.[250,1337,783,1724]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="PLATE 1. Meira diottii sp. n.: 1. Habitus; 2. surface of the pronotum (SEM); 3. detail of elytral surface (SEM)." pageId="0" pageNumber="595">Plate 1</figureCitation>
, fig. 1). Dorsal vestiture of unicolored dark scales with no metallic shine, rather or hardly imbricate, and rather elongate setae, appressed or reclined on the pronotum (
<figureCitation box="[812,888,1901,1924]" captionStart="PLATE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,238,1748,1771]" captionTargetBox="[271,1333,789,1724]" captionTargetId="figure-279@1.[250,1337,783,1724]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="PLATE 1. Meira diottii sp. n.: 1. Habitus; 2. surface of the pronotum (SEM); 3. detail of elytral surface (SEM)." pageId="0" pageNumber="595">Plate 1</figureCitation>
, fig. 2), raised or semi-erect on elytra (
<figureCitation box="[1310,1386,1901,1924]" captionStart="PLATE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,238,1748,1771]" captionTargetBox="[271,1333,789,1724]" captionTargetId="figure-279@1.[250,1337,783,1724]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="PLATE 1. Meira diottii sp. n.: 1. Habitus; 2. surface of the pronotum (SEM); 3. detail of elytral surface (SEM)." pageId="0" pageNumber="595">Plate 1</figureCitation>
, fig. 3).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="0.[151,1436,1485,2028]" pageId="0" pageNumber="595">Rostrum transverse; epistomal keel not present; pterygia hardly prominent; clypeus rather gibbous, sometimes curved at right angle on a longitudinal axis and gradually elevated on the frons.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,152,729]" pageId="1" pageNumber="596">Frons highly transverse, at times with a short longitudinal groove in the middle. Eyes oval, sub-convex. Antennae robust, with funicle articles 3-7 highly transverse, particularly so in females; club slightly wider than funicle, with first article widely cup-shaped.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,152,729]" pageId="1" pageNumber="596">Pronotum transverse, sometimes hardly so, not or only slightly wider at base than at anterior margin, rounded on its sides, with maximum width just beyond half length, disc with densely spaced deep simple punctures.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,152,729]" pageId="1" pageNumber="596">Elytra short, usually hardly rounded on sides, with striae with close spacing of punctures and interstriae narrow, flat to only slightly convex.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,152,729]" pageId="1" pageNumber="596">Legs robust; protibiae almost straight, strongly widened at apex on the external margin; metatibiae with open apical corbels.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,152,729]" pageId="1" pageNumber="596">
Penis in lateral view strongly curved towards apex (
<figureCitation box="[778,858,464,487]" captionStart="PLATE 2" captionStartId="2.[151,238,1182,1205]" captionTargetBox="[179,1400,211,1152]" captionTargetId="figure-190@2.[166,1420,194,1158]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="PLATE 2. Meira diottii sp. n.: 4. Penis, lateral view; 5. Apex of the penis, dorsal view; 6. genital armature of the internal sac, typical of the genus; 7. Supplementary genital armature of the internal sac; 8a, 8b. sensilla of the penis (SEM)." pageId="1" pageNumber="596">Plate 2</figureCitation>
, fig. 4, fig. 8a), in dorsal view gradually narrowing towards apex, then subtriangular or scutiform (
<figureCitation box="[648,725,498,521]" captionStart="PLATE 2" captionStartId="2.[151,238,1182,1205]" captionTargetBox="[179,1400,211,1152]" captionTargetId="figure-190@2.[166,1420,194,1158]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="PLATE 2. Meira diottii sp. n.: 4. Penis, lateral view; 5. Apex of the penis, dorsal view; 6. genital armature of the internal sac, typical of the genus; 7. Supplementary genital armature of the internal sac; 8a, 8b. sensilla of the penis (SEM)." pageId="1" pageNumber="596">Plate 2</figureCitation>
, fig. 5, fig. 8a), with many sensilla on sides and apex (
<figureCitation box="[1302,1378,498,521]" captionStart="PLATE 2" captionStartId="2.[151,238,1182,1205]" captionTargetBox="[179,1400,211,1152]" captionTargetId="figure-190@2.[166,1420,194,1158]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="PLATE 2. Meira diottii sp. n.: 4. Penis, lateral view; 5. Apex of the penis, dorsal view; 6. genital armature of the internal sac, typical of the genus; 7. Supplementary genital armature of the internal sac; 8a, 8b. sensilla of the penis (SEM)." pageId="1" pageNumber="596">Plate 2</figureCitation>
, figs. 8a, 8b); internal sac carrying, together with the genital armature typical of the genus (
<figureCitation box="[1065,1142,533,556]" captionStart="PLATE 2" captionStartId="2.[151,238,1182,1205]" captionTargetBox="[179,1400,211,1152]" captionTargetId="figure-190@2.[166,1420,194,1158]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="PLATE 2. Meira diottii sp. n.: 4. Penis, lateral view; 5. Apex of the penis, dorsal view; 6. genital armature of the internal sac, typical of the genus; 7. Supplementary genital armature of the internal sac; 8a, 8b. sensilla of the penis (SEM)." pageId="1" pageNumber="596">Plate 2</figureCitation>
, fig. 6), a pair of additional armatures (
<figureCitation box="[270,346,568,591]" captionStart="PLATE 2" captionStartId="2.[151,238,1182,1205]" captionTargetBox="[179,1400,211,1152]" captionTargetId="figure-190@2.[166,1420,194,1158]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="PLATE 2. Meira diottii sp. n.: 4. Penis, lateral view; 5. Apex of the penis, dorsal view; 6. genital armature of the internal sac, typical of the genus; 7. Supplementary genital armature of the internal sac; 8a, 8b. sensilla of the penis (SEM)." pageId="1" pageNumber="596">Plate 2</figureCitation>
, fig. 7).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,152,729]" pageId="1" pageNumber="596">
Spiculum ventrale sinuous at apex with manubrium elongated. Coxites of the ovipositor narrow but not elongated in the pre-apical region, sometimes converging at apex at the internal margin (
<figureCitation box="[955,1032,637,660]" captionStart="PLATE 3" captionStartId="2.[151,238,1734,1757]" captionText="PLATE 3. Meira diottii sp. n.: 9. Coxites of ovipositor; 10. Spermatheca." pageId="1" pageNumber="596">Plate 3</figureCitation>
, fig. 9). Spermatheca with cornus and ramus well developed (
<figureCitation box="[399,475,672,695]" captionStart="PLATE 3" captionStartId="2.[151,238,1734,1757]" captionText="PLATE 3. Meira diottii sp. n.: 9. Coxites of ovipositor; 10. Spermatheca." pageId="1" pageNumber="596">Plate 3</figureCitation>
, fig. 10).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,152,729]" box="[197,1093,706,729]" pageId="1" pageNumber="596">
<emphasis box="[197,514,706,729]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="596" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,507,706,729]" pageId="1" pageNumber="596">Derivation of specific name</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Dedicated to our friend and colleague Luciano Diotti.
</paragraph>
